    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-01-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-01-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="719"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d719">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">851.24/1–2545</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation by the Assistant Secretary of
                        State</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Clayton</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-01-25">January 25,
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">French Lend Lease</hi>
                </p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">Russian Lend Lease</hi>—3 C credits</p>
                <p>Secretary Morgenthau<note n="2" xml:id="d719fn2">Secretary of the Treasury
                        Morgenthau was accompanied by Harry Dexter White and Josiah E. DuBois, Jr.,
                        Assistants.</note> said that if we still felt that we should stand on an
                    interest rate of 2⅜% on these credits, he would not further oppose it.</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">Russian Long-Term Postwar Credit</hi>
                </p>
                <p>Secretary Morgenthau said that he disagreed with the view of the President and
                    the Secretary of State on this subject and felt that we should consider
                    immediately a long-term credit of $10 billion to the Russians at a low rate of
                    interest and not condition it on anything else, and stated that he felt sure
                    this is what we would do in the end.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>W[<hi rend="smallcaps">illiam</hi>] L. C[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >layton</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
